				\begin{document}$$\partial /\partial z$$\end{document} terms in the RMHD equations with forcing functions. Einaudi et al. (1996) found that the average energy dissipation increases when η\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\eta $$\end{document} is reduced (the numerical resolution is increased), as do both the peak dissipation and degree of intermittency. Dmitruk and Gómez (1997) focus on this intermittency, and identify a scaling in the number N of energy release events with a given energy E within their simulation of the form33dNdE∼E-1.5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
